# Brand system & visual consistency

## Identity first

- **Derive the palette from the brand** (logo, IG, guidelines) — not from “default Tailwind pretty colors.”
- If no assets exist yet: **propose a restrained luxury palette** (warm neutrals + one disciplined accent) and document it — don’t improvise per page.

## Tokens before screens

Before building pages, define in CSS (or tokens file):

- **Surfaces**: page, secondary, elevated/card, inverse/dark, optional accent band.
- **Text**: primary, secondary/muted, on-inverse.
- **Borders**: default, strong, on-dark.
- **Accent**: one **muted** accent (e.g. champagne) — use sparingly for highlights, not full-button fills unless intentional.
- **Radius**: 1–2 steps max site-wide (e.g. sm + md).
- **Shadow**: 1–2 elevation levels — soft, large blur, low opacity.
- **Type scale**: display (serif optional), body, eyebrow/label styles — with line-height and letter-spacing for labels.

## Implementation rules

- **No scattered hex**: components reference **semantic utilities** (`bg-surface-card`, `text-muted`, `border-line`) tied to tokens.
- **Contrast = premium**: alternate surfaces so the UI isn’t one flat sheet — still restrained.
- **Cards & inputs** share border/shadow language with the rest of the site.
- **Don’t invent unrelated colors** per section (no random blue links if the brand is warm neutral).

## Checklist before merge

- [ ] Token sheet matches brand direction  
- [ ] All new colors mapped to tokens  
- [ ] Dark sections use `on-inverse` text tokens  
- [ ] Focus states visible and on-brand  
